                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d446">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Chargé
                            <persName type="to">Sleeper</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1906-01-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 20, 1906</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 580.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The department has read with attention your
                    dispatch No. 1438 of the 13th instant, in which you report your interview with
                    the secretary of state, Mr. O’Farrill, and inclose his response to your note in
                    reference to the carrying out by Cuba of her treaty engagements in the matter of
                    the sanitation of the cities of that island.</p>
                <p>The response of the secretary of state is very unsatisfactory, in that it gives
                    little promise or assurance of an early compliance with the treaty engagements.
                    This Government thinks the time has come when there should be action. You will
                    so inform the Cuban Government.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">E. Root.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
